<section class="section fade-in">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="section-head">
      <span class="eyebrow" style="display:block; margin-bottom:1rem;">The Position</span>
      <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:1.25rem;">Two Ways to Make a Book</h2>
      <p class="lede" style="font-size:clamp(1.05rem,1.8vw,1.35rem);">
        There are two ways. <span style="color:var(--color-blue); font-style:normal; font-weight:500;">Most of what's published is the first kind. We make the second.</span>
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="two-grid">
      <article class="card" style="padding:2.2rem;">
        <p class="label" style="margin-bottom:1.1rem;">01—The Book Most Experts Write</p>
        <h3 class="h3 display-italic" style="color:var(--color-ink); margin-bottom:1.1rem;">A transcript with a cover.</h3>
        <p class="body-text">
          Fill the pages with what you already know. Outline from your talking points.
          Hire someone to "polish" your existing thinking. It ships quickly, sells modestly,
          and disappears from the conversation fast. The author is briefly proud. The reader,
          briefly bored.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="card-invert" style="padding:2.2rem;">
        <p class="eyebrow" style="display:block; margin-bottom:1.1rem;">02—The Book We Build With You</p>
        <h3 class="h3" style="font-style:italic; color:#8aa0ff; margin-bottom:1.1rem;">A behavior-change instrument with chapters.</h3>
        <p class="on-dark-soft" style="line-height:1.62;">
          An argument the reader can't refute. A transformation the reader can feel. A framework
          the reader can carry into their own work. It takes longer and asks more &mdash; and it's
          the one they're still quoting two years later.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<style>
  .two-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 1.25rem; }
  @media (max-width: 760px) { .two-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; } }
</style>
